{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476109"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:40:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:40:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13241"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13241"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.1,0.06,0.22,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111022"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5729"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93136"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44149"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111022"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parents with a two-day history of worsening asthma symptoms, including persistent dry cough and occasional shortness of breath. He has a medical history of asthma managed with regular preventer and as-needed reliever medications. He takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears alert and is able to speak in phrases. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has no cyanosis. Auscultation of the chest reveals widespread expiratory wheezes bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe receives salbutamol burst therapy (12 puffs via spacer, repeated three times at 20-minute intervals) and oral prednisolone. Four hours after initial treatment, he appears comfortable and is speaking in full sentences. His pulse rate is 95/min, respiratory rate 22/min, and he has not required salbutamol for the past three hours. However, his SpO2 is 92% on room air, with minimal wheeze on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit for overnight observation","Repeat salbutamol burst therapy","Commence continuous nebulised salbutamol","Administer inhaled ipratropium","Discharge home"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presented with a moderate asthma exacerbation and has received appropriate initial treatment with salbutamol burst therapy and oral prednisolone. After four hours of observation, he demonstrates clinical improvement with stable vital signs, comfortable breathing, and no requirement for additional bronchodilator therapy for three hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home \u003C/strong\u003Ewith an asthma action plan and GP follow-up is the most appropriate management. The child meets discharge criteria: he is clinically stable, speaking in full sentences, has normalised respiratory rate, and has been able to tolerate three hours without requiring salbutamol. Importantly, mild hypoxia (SpO2 90-94%) should not preclude discharge if the child is clinically well and has responded well to treatment, as demonstrated in this case. He has resolution of all signs of severity and a normal activity level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit for overnight observation\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered for patients who have not responded well to initial therapy, including those who require salbutamol more frequently than every three hours. Given this child\u0027s good response and stability over the observation period, admission is unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat salbutamol burst therapy\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommence continuous nebulised salbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E represents escalation of bronchodilator therapy, which would be appropriate for patients with poor response to initial treatment. These interventions are reserved for cases where the child has not achieved clinical stability or continues to require frequent bronchodilator therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister inhaled ipratropium\u003C/strong\u003E is an additional bronchodilator that would be considered for patients not responding adequately to salbutamol therapy. Since this child has responded well to initial treatment and is clinically stable, additional bronchodilator therapy is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBefore discharge, the child should receive an asthma action plan, education about inhaler technique and trigger avoidance, continuation of oral prednisolone for three days, and a follow-up plan with the long-term care provider. Parents should be advised to return if symptoms worsen or if the child requires salbutamol more frequently than every three hours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In children with asthma, the requirement for salbutamol more frequently than every three hours is a criterion that precludes discharge home.","Mild hypoxia (SpO2 90-94%) should not preclude discharge if the child is clinically well and has responded well to treatment."],"references":["National Asthma Council Australia. Australian Asthma Handbook, Version 2.0. National Asthma Council Australia, Melbourne, 2019. Available from:\u00a0http://asthmahandbook.org.au","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital, Melbourne, Australia, Clinical Practice Guideline on Acute Asthma, [Internet, last updated December 2020; cited 2025 Aug 5], Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Asthma_acute/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93136"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13241"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93136"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-06T19:26:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-06T19:37:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5729"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111022"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"